inference:
Let $I$ be the incenter of $\triangle ABC$, and let $O_A$, $O_B$, and $O_C$ be the centers of the excircles tangent to $\overline{BC}$, $\overline{AC}$, and $\overline{AB}$, respectively. Let $r$ be the inradius of $\triangle ABC$, and let $r_A$, $r_B$, and $r_C$ be the radii of the excircles.

[asy]
unitsize(0.8cm);
pair A,B,C,I,OA,OB,OC;
A = (0,1);
B = (-1,0);
C = (1,0);
I = incenter(A,B,C);
OA = extension(B,C,A + reflect(B,C)*(A),A + reflect(B,C)*(A) + dir(110));
OB = extension(A,C,B + reflect(A,C)*(B),B + reflect(A,C)*(B) + dir(110));
OC = extension(A,B,C + reflect(A,B)*(C),C + reflect(A,B)*(C) + dir(110));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(incircle(A,B,C));
draw(Circle(OA,abs(OA - B)));
draw(Circle(OB,abs(OB - A)));
draw(Circle(OC,abs(OC - A)));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SW);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$I$",I,NE);
label("$O_A$",OA,NE);
label("$O_B$",OB,NW);
label("$O_C$",OC,S);
[/asy]

Since $AB = AC$, we have $r_B = r_C$. Let $s$ be the semiperimeter of $\triangle ABC$.  Then by the formula for the inradius and the exradii, we have
\[r = \frac{K}{s}, \quad r_A = \frac{K}{s - a}, \quad r_B = r_C = \frac{K}{s - b} = \frac{K}{s - c},\]where $K$ is the area of $\triangle ABC$.

Since the excircle tangent to $\overline{BC}$ is internally tangent to $\omega$, the distance from $O_A$ to the line $BC$ is equal to $r + r_A$. Since the other two excircles are externally tangent to $\omega$, the distance from $O_B$ to the line $AC$ and the distance from $O_C$ to the line $AB$ are both equal to $r_B - r$.

